text: The description with the trailer should specify that this was a team of US ARMY Special Forces, aka Green Berets. Only Green Berets are officially designated as Special Forces. The SF Regiment was formed in 1952, and since the mid-80s, every soldier who passes the SF Qualification Course is awarded a curved patch known as a "tab" which says SPECIAL FORCES, and is worn on the left shoulder above the unit patch an AIRBORNE tab (and RANGER tab, if he has that qualification as well ). All other troops assigned to US Special Operations Command (USSOCOM), such as Navy SEALs, Army Rangers, MARSOC Marines, and Air Force Pararescue and Combat Controllers, and various support troops, are officially collectively called US Special Operations Forces, or SOF. This is the first recent war movie made about Green Berets instead of Navy SEALs. Only Green Berets were capable of conducting this mission, because they are the ONLY US SOF trained, qualified, and tasked to conduct this specific type of operation with indigenous forces, which is known as Unconventional Warfare (UW). Only Green Berets are required to learn a foreign language and become subject matter experts in their unit's designated regional Area of Operations. Unlike young SEALs, Green Berets rarely brag or seek fame or glory by writing books. They don't lie about their accomplishments like Chris Kyle, the proven fraud behind "American Sniper". And they don't celebrate a  horrific failure where a poorly planned mission ends in a young Lieutenant getting himself and 21 others killed, which is the story behind "Lone Survivor ". You won't see a similar movie about an epic fuck up by a team of Green Berets which gets them and a lot of their buddies killed because it has never happened. That's because they are masters at conducting thorough and meticulous operational planning.
